\subsection{AGE EFFECT}\label{age-effect}}

Run ordered categorical model without 56y old man, same results: -no
effect of age bA; -linear effect of age from 0 to 26, no sign of lack of
data from 0 to 5

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{dat <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{( }\DataTypeTok{D =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}
             \DataTypeTok{N =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{N }\DecValTok{-1}\NormalTok{, }
             \DataTypeTok{L =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{L , }
             \DataTypeTok{Q =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Q ,    }\CommentTok{#n questionnaire items}
             \DataTypeTok{R =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{R ,    }\CommentTok{#n image recognition items}
             \DataTypeTok{A =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{A [d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{A }\OperatorTok{<=}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{50}\NormalTok{] , }\CommentTok{#round age}
             \DataTypeTok{Y_l =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y_l [}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y_l) }\OperatorTok{!=}\StringTok{ "19586"}\NormalTok{,] ,}
             \DataTypeTok{Y_q =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y_q [}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y_q) }\OperatorTok{!=}\StringTok{ "19586"}\NormalTok{,] , }\CommentTok{#answers questionnaire}
             \DataTypeTok{Y_r =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y_r [}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y_r) }\OperatorTok{!=}\StringTok{ "19586"}\NormalTok{,] , }\CommentTok{#answers picture recognition}
             \DataTypeTok{O =} \KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{0} \OperatorTok{:}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{26}\NormalTok{ ) ,}
             \DataTypeTok{alpha =} \KeywordTok{rep}\NormalTok{( }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{0}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{26}\NormalTok{ ) }\DecValTok{-1}\NormalTok{ ) )}

\#simulate with missing ages So I run the same model on simulated data
measuring effect all the way to 50 years, with sigmoid age relation
within the known range. The age specific effect keep growing after the
data are not available anymore, but there is a clear difference between
the deltas for ages where the increase of knowledge is more marked and
where there is no information. When plotting the expected total effect
at each age, there is no sign anymore of the sigmoid relation of
knowledge to age at the beginning of the curve. But importantly, the
total effect of age bA is very strong.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sim_data <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{simulation}\NormalTok{( }\DataTypeTok{N =} \DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{M =} \DecValTok{300}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{beta_A =} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{age_eff =} \StringTok{"sigmoid"}\NormalTok{)}
\CommentTok{#with each year a step}
\NormalTok{dat <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{( }\DataTypeTok{D =}\NormalTok{ sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{n_dimensions,}
             \DataTypeTok{N =}\NormalTok{ sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{N , }
             \DataTypeTok{L =}\NormalTok{ sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{M , }
             \DataTypeTok{Q =} \DecValTok{50}\NormalTok{,         }\CommentTok{#n questionnaire items}
             \DataTypeTok{R =}\NormalTok{ sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{M}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,}\CommentTok{#n image recognition items}
             \DataTypeTok{A =} \KeywordTok{round}\NormalTok{ (sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{A) , }\CommentTok{#round age}
             \DataTypeTok{S =}\NormalTok{ sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{S,}
             \DataTypeTok{Y_l =}\NormalTok{ sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y ,}
             \DataTypeTok{Y_q =}\NormalTok{ sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y[,}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{50}\NormalTok{] ,           }\CommentTok{#answers questionnaire}
             \DataTypeTok{Y_r =}\NormalTok{ sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Y[,}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\NormalTok{(sim_data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{M}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)],  }\CommentTok{#answers picture recognition}
             \DataTypeTok{O =} \KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{0} \OperatorTok{:}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{50}\NormalTok{ ),}
             \DataTypeTok{alpha =} \KeywordTok{rep}\NormalTok{( }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{50}\NormalTok{) )}
\NormalTok{             )}
\NormalTok{m_ord_s <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{stan}\NormalTok{( }\DataTypeTok{file =}  \StringTok{"../models/2_model_code_ord_age.stan"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{data=}\NormalTok{dat , }\DataTypeTok{chains=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{cores=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This obviously emerges when comparing the individual effects aK on
knowledge from the models with linear vs ordered categorical effect of
age. In the ordered categorical model, since age has no effect, aK
captures all the variation between ages and correlates with age itself.
In the linear model, bA captures most of the effect of age and aK takes
care of the individual variation, and does not correlate stronglu with
age:

\begin{Shaded}

\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{A [ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{A }\OperatorTok{<=}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{50}\NormalTok{ ], aKs, }\DataTypeTok{xlab =} \StringTok{"Age"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ylab =} \StringTok{"Individual effect on knowledge"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{main =} \StringTok{"Ordered categorical"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{post <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{extract.samples}\NormalTok{(m_lin)}
\NormalTok{aKs <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{apply}\NormalTok{(post}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{aK, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, mean)}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{A [ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{A }\OperatorTok{<=}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{50}\NormalTok{ ], aKs, }\DataTypeTok{xlab =} \StringTok{"Age"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ylab =} \StringTok{"Individual effect on knowledge"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{main =} \StringTok{"Linear"}\NormalTok{)}

\hypertarget{dimensions}{%
\subsection{DIMENSIONS}\label{dimensions}}

First thing I did Monday morning was to check what was going on with the
dimensions. But the model was not recognizing multiple dimensions
anymore. It turns out that when the data from freelists, questions and
image recognition are analyzed together, the model with only one
dimension is preferred.

\CommentTok{#run the model with 1:3 number of dimensions}

\NormalTok{  dat <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{( }\DataTypeTok{D =}\NormalTok{ D[i],    }\CommentTok{#loop through dimensions}

               \DataTypeTok{R =}\NormalTok{ d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{R ,    }\CommentTok{#n image recognition items}
               \DataTypeTok{A =} \KeywordTok{standardize}\NormalTok{(d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{A) , }\CommentTok{#standardized age}

First, let's focus on the results of the model using only the freelist
data and, for now, three dimensions.

To better unedrstand how the different dimensions capture variation
among individuals in knowledge, let's plot the estimated knowledge K in
each dimension against all other dimensions.

In this model I introduced an intercept for sex. Interestingly, the
relation between the dimensions changes.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{post_d <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{extract.samples}\NormalTok{(m_dl[[}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{]])}

\CommentTok{#check the correlation between dimensions}
\KeywordTok{par}\NormalTok{( }\DataTypeTok{mfrow =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{( }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{))}
\CommentTok{#knowledge}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{apply}\NormalTok{( post_d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{K[,,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{], }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, mean), }\KeywordTok{apply}\NormalTok{( post_d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{K[,,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{], }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, mean),}
     \DataTypeTok{xlab =} \StringTok{"K 1"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ylab =} \StringTok{"K 2"}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{apply}\NormalTok{( post_d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{K[,,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{], }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, mean), }\KeywordTok{apply}\NormalTok{( post_d}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{K[,,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{], }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, mean),}
     \DataTypeTok{xlab =} \StringTok{"K 1"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ylab =} \StringTok{"K 3"}\NormalTok{)}

\includegraphics{04_23_meet_Richard_files/figure-latex/dimensions in freelists knowledge-1.pdf}

Let's see the effect of age and sex. Age seem to correlate positively
with knowledge in all dimensions, but when sex is not included it does
affect more one than the other dimensions. Compared with the model with
no dimensions, age seems to be less important, though.

dimensions, where the easy ones vary by dimension - which makes sense,
cause even when named, the hard items are named only once, whereas the
simple items named many times give space to variation.
